# Overview

The raw data here represent NWChem-format files for the Effective Core Potential (ECP) framework defined by the user. These files are used to construct both standard ECP and Hybrid Pseudopotential Hamiltonian (HPH) models within JaQMC.

# Hybrid Pseudopotential Hamiltonian (HPH)

HPH is constructed by combining the local and L2 channels from the PH (pseudo-Hamiltonian) framework and the residual nonlocal channels (e.g., s and p) from the ECP framework. 

The residual nonlocal channels for Sc atom in the NWChem format is presented as Sc.0.21_187_nl.nwchem

# Truncated Semilocal form of HPH

The truncated semilocal form of HPH is obtained by presenting in the format of standard Effective Core Potential (ECP). It is obatined by limiting the angular momentum expansion of the HPH to a finite cutoff lmax. 

The truncated hybrid potential with lmax = 7 is a semilocal pseudopotential, constructed such that:

<l|v_truncated|l> = <l|v_hybrid|l> for l ≤ lmax

More generally, for any truncated variant:
	•	for l ≤ lmax, the truncated potential matches the corresponding channels of the full HPH
	•	for l > lmax, the contributions are neglected

The truncated semilocal form of HPH is obtained by limiting the angular momentum expansion of the hybrid pseudopotential to a finite cutoff lmax. 

Each truncated variant (tr2–tr7) corresponds to a different choice of lmax:
	•	tr2 → lmax = 2
	•	tr3 → lmax = 3
	•	tr4 → lmax = 4
	•	tr5 → lmax = 5
	•	tr6 → lmax = 6
	•	tr7 → lmax = 7

The files are:

Sc.0.21_187_tr2.nwchem
Sc.0.21_187_tr3.nwchem
Sc.0.21_187_tr4.nwchem
Sc.0.21_187_tr5.nwchem
Sc.0.21_187_tr6.nwchem
Sc.0.21_187_tr7.nwchem

These truncated potentials provide a hierarchy of semilocal approximations to the full HPH, allowing systematic assessment of the role of higher angular momentum channels.

In principle, increasing lmax should improve agreement with the full HPH, although in practice higher truncations may introduce increased variance and reduced numerical stability in QMC calculations.

# Purpose

The tr2–tr7 variants are included to benchmark the current HPH implementation against truncated semilocal forms.

By varying lmax, we can:
	•	systematically evaluate how well truncated potentials reproduce the behavior of the full HPH
	•	assess the contribution of higher angular momentum channels
	•	compare accuracy and stability across different truncation levels

In principle, higher lmax (e.g., tr7) should more closely approximate the full HPH.

# Observations

Based on current benchmark results for:
	•	Sc ionization energy
	•	ScO dissociation energy

we observe:
	•	tr2–tr4 show good performance, with accurate energies and relatively low variance
	•	tr5–tr7 show reduced accuracy and higher variance

Although higher truncation levels include more angular momentum channels, they introduce increased numerical noise and instability in QMC calculations.